{
  "card_id": "uptrend",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Uptrend",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A market condition where prices consistently form higher highs and higher lows, indicating bullish momentum. The uptrend remains valid as long as price holds above the low of the most recent pullback after an impulsive move breaks a prior high.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Price forms a sequence of higher highs and higher lows.",
    "Price breaks previous major highs to the upside, creating Break of Structure (BOS).",
    "Price remains above the most recent major low; a break below that low signals a potential trend reversal.",
    "Major lows are identified as the lowest point of the bullish wave that initiated the upward move leading to a BOS.",
    "Distinguish impulsive moves (in trend direction) from pullbacks (counter-trend moves).",
    "Confirm that each new high is higher than the previous swing high and each new low is higher than the previous swing low.",
    "Validate the uptrend is intact as long as price holds above the low of the most recent pullback after an impulsive move breaks a prior high."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "In an uptrend, traders seek buying opportunities. Pullbacks to higher lows offer potential entry points, with stop losses placed below recent pullback lows. A break of a major high (BOS) signals trend continuation, while a break below a major low indicates a potential reversal. As long as price holds above the most recent major low, the bullish bias remains valid.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Misidentifying major lows can lead to trading on the wrong side of the market, mistaking a trend reversal for a continuation, or entering late after the trend has already reversed.",
    "Assuming an uptrend exists based solely on higher highs without confirming higher lows.",
    "Mislabeling a valid uptrend period as sideways or downtrend when both higher highs and higher lows are still present.",
    "Assuming an uptrend solely because price is moving upward, without verifying higher highs and higher lows.",
    "Failing to wait for an impulsive move to break a prior high before confirming trend continuation."
  ],
